<main>

<section>
<h2>1. Strict Safety Regulations</h2>
<p>
Baby beds must meet strict government safety standards to protect infants.
Manufacturers have to follow rules about spacing between bars, mattress
support, paint safety, and overall structural strength. Testing and
certification add significant costs before the product can even be sold.
</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>2. High-Quality Materials</h2>
<p>
Many baby beds are made from solid wood or durable engineered wood so they
can safely hold a baby for years. Manufacturers often use non-toxic finishes
and stronger hardware, which increases production costs compared to normal
furniture.
</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>3. Research and Product Testing</h2>
<p>
Companies invest in research, design, and safety testing. Cribs are tested
for weight limits, shaking, impact resistance, and long-term durability.
These tests help prevent accidents but add to the overall price.
</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>4. Convertible Designs</h2>
<p>
Many modern baby beds convert into toddler beds or even full-size beds.
This extra functionality requires more parts and engineering, which can
raise the price but also makes the bed usable for several years.
</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>5. Branding and Retail Markups</h2>
<p>
Like many baby products, well-known brands charge more because parents
often prefer trusted names when it comes to safety. Retail stores and
shipping costs also increase the final price you see.
</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>
While baby beds can seem expensive, much of the cost comes from safety
requirements, strong materials, and long-term durability. These factors
help ensure that babies sleep in a secure and reliable environment.
</p>
</section>

